Monte Carlo Markov Chain in Julia

Author: Giuseppe Ragusa

Introduction

Julia provides some very well written packages for Baysian estimation.

The most useful are Lora and Mamba.

Lora provides a generic engine for Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) inference. It is undergoing a major upgrade and some feature stands up, such as the ability to use automatic differentiation for samplers that require the gradient of the log-target.

Mamba is an open platform for the implementation and application of MCMC methods to perform Bayesian analysis. It provides a framework for (1) specification of hierarchical models through stated relationships between data, parameters, and statistical distributions; (2) block-updating of parameters with samplers provided, defined by the user, or available from other packages; (3) execution of sampling schemes; and (4) posterior inference. It is intended to give users access to all levels of the design and implementation of MCMC simulators to particularly aid in the development of new methods.

Example: robust linear model

We will illustrate how to use Lora and Mamba for obtaining draws from a posterior distribution by using a simple example. Once we have understood the logic we will move to a Kalman Filter based likelihood.

The log-target

The log-target is the logarithm of the numerator of the posterior distribution. Using the standard notation, if \[post(\theta) = \gamma(\theta)p(\theta)/Z\] is the posterior, the log-target is given by \[logtarget(\theta) = \log \gamma(\theta) + \log p(\theta)\].

Let's consider the linear model with \(t\) distributed errors. The data \(\{y_{i}, x_{i}\}\), \(i=1,\ldots,n\) are realization of an iid sequence of random vector \((Y_{i}, X_{i})\) whose distribution is \[Y_{i} | X_{i} = x_{i} \sim t(\nu, \alpha + \beta x_i, \sigma^2),\] where \(t(\nu, \mu, \sigma^2)\) denote the distribution of a random variable so defined \[Z=\mu+\sigma\epsilon\sqrt{\frac{\nu-2}{\nu}},\quad t(\nu),\quad\nu>2,\] where \(t(\nu)\) denotes the t-student distribution with \(\nu\) degrees of freedom.

The likelihood function for this model is (let \(\theta = (\alpha, \beta, \sigma)\)) \[ \gamma(\theta) = \sigma^{-n} \prod_{i=1}^n \left( 1+\frac{(y_i-\alpha-\beta x_i)^2}{\nu\sigma^2}\right)^{-(\nu+1)/2}. \]

We use an improper prior \[ p(\theta) \propto \sigma^{-1} \] giving thus the following log-target \[ logtarget(\theta) = -(n+1)\log \sigma - (\nu+1)/2 \sum_{i=1}^n \log\left( 1+\frac{(y_i-\alpha-\beta x_i)^2}{\nu\sigma^2}\right). \]

We start by generating data according to the model. We use the following parameterization

using Distributions
ν = 3; n = 100; α = 0.0; β = 0.5; σ² = 1.0
d = TDist(ν)
srand(123333)
x = rand(d, n)./sqrt(ν/(ν-2))
y = rand(d, n)./sqrt(ν/(ν-2)) .* sqrt(σ²) + α + β*x

The OLS estimates of \((\alpha, \beta)\) are

bols = [ones(n) x]\y

the estimated variance

s² = sumabs2(y-[ones(n) x]*bols)/(n-1)

We will use these values to initialize the MCMC algorithm.

We now need to code the function that evaluates the log-target at \(\theta\).

function logtarget(theta)
   n  = length(y)
   α  = theta[1]
   β  = theta[2]
   σ² = theta[3]
   -(n+1)*log(sqrt(σ²)) - (ν+1)/2*sum(log(1+(y-α-β*x).^2/(ν*σ²)))
end

This function would not however work. The problem is that both \(\sigma\) is restricted to be positive. In order to avoid problems with eventual proposed negative values, we will reparameterize the log-target in terms of \(\theta = (\alpha, \beta, \log(\sigma))\). This amount rewrite the log-target as follows.

function logtarget(theta)
   n  = length(y)
   α  = theta[1]
   β  = theta[2]
   σ² = exp(theta[3])
   -(n+1)*log(sqrt(σ²)) - (ν+1)/2*sum(log(1+(y-α-β*x).^2/(ν*σ²)))
end

Lora

using Lora

### Define the parameter via BasicContMuvParameter
### The input arguments for BasicContMuvParameter are:
### 1) the variable key,
### 2) the log-target

p = BasicContMuvParameter(:p, logtarget=logtarget)

### Define the model using the likelihood_model generator
### The second argument informs the likelihood_model
### generator that p.index has not been set

model = likelihood_model(p, false)

### Define a Metropolis-Hastings sampler with an identity
### covariance matrix scaled by 10

sampler = MH(ones(3)/10)

### Set MCMC sampling range

mcrange = BasicMCRange(nsteps=100000, burnin=1000)

### Set initial values for simulation

v0 = Dict(:p=>[bols; log(sqrt(s²)) ])

### Specify job to be run

job = BasicMCJob(model, sampler, mcrange, v0,
                 tuner=VanillaMCTuner(verbose=true))

### Run the simulation

run(job)

Mamba

using Mamba
## Data
data = Dict(
  :x => x,
  :y => y,
  :n => length(y)
)

function plogtarget(theta)
   n  = data[:n]
   α  = theta[1]
   β  = theta[2]
   σ  = exp(theta[3])
   -(n+1)*log(σ) - (ν+1)/2*sum(log(1+(data[:y]-α-β*data[:x]).^2/(ν*σ^2)))
end


n = 50000
burnin = 1000

sim = Chains(n, 3, names = ["α", "β", "σ"]);

theta = RWMVariate([bols; log(sqrt(s²))], [0.1, 0.1, 0.1], plogtarget,
                   proposal = Normal)

for i in 1:n
  sample!(theta)
  sim[i, :, 1] = [theta[1:2]; exp(theta[3])]
end

sim is an object of class Chain for which several methods are defined.

describe produces a summary of the posterior information.

Linear State Space Model

Consider the following State Space model:

\begin{align*} x_{t+1} & =g_{0}+g_{1}x_{t}+m_{1}\varepsilon_{t+1},\quad\varepsilon_{t}\sim N(0,\sigma_{\varepsilon}^{2})\\ y_{t} & =h_{0}+h_{1}x_{t}+\eta_{t},\quad\eta_{t}\sim N(0,\sigma_{\eta}^{2}) \end{align*}

The objective is to estimate \[ \theta=\{g_{0},g_{1},m_{1},\sigma_{\varepsilon},h_{0},h_{1},\sigma_{\eta}\} \] from a realization of the observable \(\{y\}_{t=1}^{T}\). This can be done in \(3\) steps:

  1. Apply the Kalman's filter
  2. Calculate the likelihood functions
  3. Apply a the MH algorithm to get the posterior distribution of the parameter

Likelihood

The function kfloglik evaluate the log-likelihood of the space state model. While this function will only work for scalar SS model, for our purposes will suffice.

function kfloglik(x0, s0, g0, g1, sigmae, h0, h1,  sigmaeta, y)
    T = size(y, 1)
    ## x_{t|t}
    filt  = zeros((T+1),1)
    Ptt   = zeros((T+1),1)
    Ptt[1,1] = s0
    pred = zeros((T+1),1)
    Pt = zeros((T+1),1)

    for j=1:T
        ## Predictions step
        pred[j,1] = g0+g1*filt[j,1]
        Pt[j,1] = g1*Ptt[j,1]*g1+sigmae^2
        ## Updating step
        K = Pt[j,1]*h1*(h1^2*Pt[j,1]+sigmaeta^2)^(-1)
        filt[j+1,1] = pred[j,1] + K*(y[j,1]-h0-h1*pred[j,1])
        Ptt[j+1,1] = Pt[j,1] - K*(h1*Pt[j,1])
    end

    mu = h0+h1*pred
    sd = h1*Pt*h1+sigmaeta.^2
    -T*log(2*pi)/2+sum(-log(sd[1:T])/2-(y-mu[1:T]).^2./(2*sd[1:T]))
end

Generate fake data

We generate data from the SS space model. We choose the following parameterization: \[ g_0 = 0, g_1 = 0.9, \sigma_{\epsilon} = 1, h_0 = 0.2, h_1=.5, \sigma_{\eta} = 0.3. \]

srand(1234)  ## set seed
n = 240
theta0 = [0; 0.9; 1; 0.2; 0.5; 0.3]
x = zeros(n+1)
y = zeros(n+1)


for j = 2:(n+1)
  x[j] = theta0[1]+theta0[2]*x[j-1] + randn()*theta0[3]
  y[j] = theta0[4]+theta0[5]*x[j] + randn()*theta0[6]
end
y = y[2:end]
x = x[2:end]
using Plots
gadfly()
Plots.plot(y, lab = "observation")
Plots.plot!(x, lab = "states")

 

Restricted Log-likelihood

To make things a little more interesting we are going to assume that we need to estimate only a subset of \(\theta\). In particular, we will estimate only \(g_0, g_1, \sigma_{\epsilon}\). In order to do so, it will suffice to define logtarget to take as input a \(3\times 1\) vector and call kfloglik with the fixed values for the other parameters. In particular, we will set \(h_0 = 0\), \(h_1 = 1\) and \(\sigma_{\eta}=0.3\).

function logtarget(theta)
    ## theta = (g0, g1, sigmae)
    g0 = theta[1]
    g1 = exp(theta[2])/(1+exp(theta[2]));
    sigmae = exp(theta[3])
    s0 = sigmae^2/(1-g1^2)
    kfloglik(0.0, s0, g0, g1, sigmae, 0.2, 0.5, 0.3, y)
end

Notice that we are assuming flat prior on \(\theta\). Changing the cose to allow for informative priors is a matter of summing \(\log p(\theta)\) to the value returned by the call to kfloglik.

Maximum likelihood

Maximizing the log-likelihood can be done by optimize from the package Optim. Optim is under development (check the github repository). The code below is tested against the master branch. To install the master branch of Optim follow these steps:

Pkg.add("Optim")
Pkg.checkout("Optim")

Once the master branch is installed you can load the package as you would normally.

using Optim

optimize takes many arguments and allows optimizing a function with different algorithms (BFGS, L-BFGS, Nelder Mean, etc.).

A typical call to optimize is

optimize(f, par0, method)

where f is the function to be optimized and par0 is the vector of starting value for the selected method

Importantly, optimize will assume the f is to be minimized. So, if we were to do this

optimize(logtarget, [0., .5, .5], BFGS())

will be calculating the minimum likelihood estimator!

A way to circumvent this problem is to define the function to be minimized as the negative log-target:

negative_logtarget(theta) = -logtarget(theta)

and then optimize over negative_logtarget

out = optimize(negative_logtarget, [0, .5, .5])

Optim has many functions to extract information from the object out.

julia> Optim.minimum(out)

231.01655831397576
julia> init0 = Optim.minimizer(out)
3-element Array{Float64,1}:
 0.0226079 
 2.40374   
 0.00873056

init0 contains the ML estimates which we will use to start the MH algorithm. chain. values can be used to initialized the MCMC chain. But we also need a value for the hessian to properly scale the proposal distribution.

julia> using Calculus

julia> invH = inv(hessian(negative_logtarget, Optim.minimizer(out)))
3x3 Array{Float64,2}:
  0.00429792  -0.00170108   7.98027e-5
 -0.00170108   0.116398    -0.00483797
  7.98027e-5  -0.00483797   0.00447374

The inverse of the hessian of the (negative) loglikelihood can also be used as an estimator of the asymptotic variance of the MLE.

Metropolis Hastings

using Mamba
## Data
data = Dict(
  :y => y,
  :n => length(y)
)


n = 50000
burnin = 1000

sim = Chains(n, 3, names = ["g0", "g1", "sigmae"]);


function logtarget(theta)
    g0 = theta[1]
    g1 = exp(theta[2])/(1+exp(theta[2]));
    sigmae = exp(theta[3])
    s0 = sigmae^2/(1-g1^2)
    kfloglik(0.0, s0, g0, g1, sigmae, 0.2, 0.5, 0.3, y)
end


theta = RWMVariate(out.minimum, diag(invH), logtarget, proposal = Normal)

for i in 1:n
  sample!(theta)
  sim[i, :, 1] = [theta[1]; exp(theta[2])/(1 + exp(theta[2])); exp(theta[3])]
end

The acceptance rate of the chain is

A graphical inspection of the traceplot is the starting point for verifying that the MH algorithm has converged. A more formal assessment of convergence can be based on statistical tests. There exists many of these tests.

The simpler one to grasp is the Geweke diagnostic. This method is based on splitting the chain in two windows, say the first 10% of that chain and the last 50%. The sample mean is calculated in these two windows and a test of equality between the two means is performed. The test is a standard t-test.

gewekediag(sim) |> showall
